                    <td width="100%" colspan="2" valign="top" align="left">
                      <div align="center">
                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%" bgcolor="#004242">
                              <p align="center" style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 150%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><b><font size="2" face="Tahoma" color="#FFFFFF">DESCRIPTION</font></b></td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr><td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td width="100%">
                              <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">
Looming over the pit in the Field of Bone is the infamous Kurn's Tower.  Standing tall above the undead wastes, many adventurers seek to reach its pinnacle and defeat the evil there.  Unfortunately, Kurn's Tower is actually a little bit misleading from the outside.  The more difficult mobs in this zone are actually in the tunnels below it, where the Burynai have begun their assault on this abandoned home of the undead.  Above ground there are four floors, and below there is the basement, with a large drop that leads to the Burynai depths below.  Obviously the best place to bind for this zone would be across the Field of Bone in the city of Cabilis.  Since the zone is filled largely with the undead, any of you with the ward line of undead spells are at an advantage at the earlier levels.  Hold off on coming into the tower until you are about level seven.  And consider waiting until the early teens before proceeding to the depths below.  
<br><br>
Kurn's Tower is a dungeon that really has few landmarks.  The upper three floors are very similar and there's hardly anything characteristic about each of them separately.  The Japanese-style architecture is prevalent on all levels.  The basement follows the same model, except the corridors are more compact and complex, and there seems to be a lot more damage to the tower due to the Burynai legions.  After following the winding paths of the basement, you find one of two pits in the floor, and these lead to the caverns below.  I'll warn again when I speak specifically of this area, but falling in the pit does roughly 150+ damage.  Not only that, but the fall is one-way.  You'll have to do a bit of searching to find the way out into the field of bone.  With that in mind, there is one entrance and two exits from Kurn's Tower.  The entrance also serves as an exit, but the cavern level zone line is a one-way ticket to Field of Bone.
<br><br>
After studying the maps, and honestly I'd print them out for the lower levels, it should be safe for you to enter.  A note on the entrance from FoB, it does not matter which way you head at the entrance, they both lead to the foyer of the Tower.  After zoning in, take note that there are no spawns in the foyer here.  The back wall is generally a good spot to pull mobs.  Keep in mind however that roughly twenty feet in front of you, guard scalebones spawn.  This first floor is extremely large.  There is an extreme cavernous feel to it, and luckily this makes the mobs spread fairly far apart.  The back wall here is where those who are lvl 7-11 should fight.  Simply put your backs to the wall, and start sending the puller out into the main area to grab single scalebones.  This method is fairly safe since the zone is within a few steps.  The main area here has a couple of small, dead end rooms (they almost seem like cells) that have a couple of spawns to draw out.  Also take note of the secret room to the back end of the main area, just to the left of the hallway down to the basement.  There are two ways to go once you feel that scalebones are getting old:  up or down.  Going up requires you to head to the west end of the large main chamber and following the staircase upward.  You will find mobs all over here, and they're far enough apart to avoid entirely.  After making your way up to the second floor, you cross the walkways above the main chamber to a split path.  It doesn't matter if you take the left or right path, they're almost symmetrical and both have staircases that lead up to the 3rd floor.  Keep in mind, the same mobs roam from the 1st floor all the way until the third (with a few lesser charbone and icebones thron in for good measure,) so it's virtually the same if you just pull to the front area.  The two staircases that lead up to the third floor from the second, both are essentially along the same hallway, and in the middle of that hallway there are twin staircases leading midway up to a rectangular pathway.  In the middle of this pathway there are two rooms, one of which being the barracks.  Two room also line the outer rim of the pathways and house only scalebones and skeletons.  Only when you reach the fourth and final floor, (the stairs leading up are near the stairs leading own to the second floor) does a different type of mob appear.  There is a large room, entirely distinguishable from the others here.  For starters it's about three times larger than the adjacent rooms.  Secondly, it has some tables turned over and a wall caved in.  This is what's known as the cafeteria.  The undead crusader spawns here but the room is usually teeming with the greater scalebones just like the rest of the upper floors.  Assuming that you're finished with the upper floors, it's time to get to the heart of the dungeon: the depths below.
<br><br>
Once you're roughly level 13 and with a group, go back to the main chamber and head to the northeast corner, (by the hidden door I was telling you about) and head down the staircase.  This is what's generally referred to as the basement.  The mobs here stay fairly similar (skeletons) with the addition of the Burynai.  One thing you'll notice is that the burrowers and excavators inside the Tower are different than the ones outside.  The Field of Bone Burynai are of the warrior class.  The Burynai inside the Tower are both necromancers and Shadow Knights.  Watch for harm touch, it can easily take tanks to half health very quickly.  The mobs here are very easy to pull on an individual or pair basis.  There are very few roamers and most Burynai are stationary.  A group of 3 or so can make great headway here so long as they use a little common sense in their pulls.  There's also a secret here, some rooms (I won't say which or the lot of you would camp them) have an invisible wall in the doorway.  If you end up grabbing more than you can chew, get into one of these rooms and cast on the mobs from inside without fear of being injured.  These rooms shouldn't be abused for two reasons: if you need to cheat to level, you don't deserve to be playing EQ.  The second reason is that if people start abusing this 'bug,' not only will it be removed, but you'll most likely be suspended/terminated. [Note to Wraith: you might want to delete this part bud, I don't know if you want folks server-wide knowing about it]  Like with other guides I write, I'm not going to go into detail the different paths you can take in the basement, it's just too complicated and a map would serve you better. There's quite a few areas to camp here, so finding a spot to pull to shouldn't be too difficult.  With that in mind, the mobs here are all the same, although near the west end of the area the mobs tend to be more excavators than burrowers.  The only spawn of note on this floor is the undead jester, who rarely drops the Iksar Berserker Club.  If you turn your attention to the south wall of the basement as well as the northwest corner (right next to the undead jester spawn,) you'll find two large holes.  Both of these can be jumped (I suggest levitation) down into to reach the bottom of this zone: the burynai caves.  
<br><br>
Keep in mind that by jumping down here, you'll be taking quite a bit of damage (well above 150+.)  Once down here, there's some low to upper level 20's burynai and undead you can kill.  There's also a few named spawns that don't drop anything worth camping (other than to sell, they're not terrible items, but nothing worth holding onto at the upper 20's level you need to be at to camp them.)  I wouldn't suggest making a move into the lower levels for experience gain.  Areas such as the Sarnak Fortress or Goblin Caves in the Lake of Ill Omen are much easier to control and more reliable.  Since you can't make your way back up the holes you jumped down, you'll need to make your way to the far east of the zone for a rather large zone to the Field of Bone.
<br><br>
I feel that this isn't an entirely bad zone to play in, but it really serves as an alternative to non-power gamers that get fed up with the Field of Bone.  I don't suggest moving down to the burynai caves simply because the level difference is a little more than drastic, and the reward is definitely not up to par.  This zone also has extreme potential for trains, but since not many people utilize the zone it isn't too much of a threat.
<br><br>
<b>Extras</b>
<br><br>
Ward Undead spells work fantastic here.
<br><br>
Remember that it's nearly impossible to be invisible to everything in the zone since it's a combination of undead and alive.
<br><br>
<b>Arafel<br>
Fennin Ro</b>
